-- South African Stocks Fall 0.2%, Led Down by Pinnacle Technology, SABMiller
-- Garth Theunissen
-- 2010-07-20T10:27:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/south-african-stocks-fall-0-2-led-down-by-pinnacle-technology-sabmiller.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  fell 61.47, or 0.2 percent, to 27,268.28 at 11:44
a.m. in Johannesburg, a second day of losses.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Aquarius Platinum Ltd.  (AQP SJ), the fourth-largest
producer of the metal, rose 3 rand, or 12 percent, to 29 rand,
the steepest climb since Aug. 3, 2009. Aquarius was raised to
“buy” from “sell” at Canaccord Genuity Corp.  
 South Africa’s government said a mines safety directive
wasn’t intended to halt mining. The shares sank yesterday after
the government announced new rules affecting mines in the
platinum-rich North West province, following the death of five
miners this month.  
 BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, rose as much as 4.78 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 216 rand,
and last traded up 0.3 percent at 211.80 rand. Copper for three-
month delivery on the London Metal Exchange climbed as much as
1.5 percent to $6,610 a metric ton. Barclays Capital raised BHP
to “overweight” from “equalweight.”  
 Ellies Holdings Ltd.  (ELI SJ), the maker of satellite
television equipment, advanced 10 cents, or 6.5 percent, to 1.65
rand. The company said full-year revenue increased 18 percent to
1.16 billion rand ($211 million).  
 Pinnacle Technology Holdings Ltd.  (PNC SJ), a technology-
services company, fell 10 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 4.20 rand,
reversing yesterday’s gain. Pinnacle said it acquired Axiz
Technology Ltd. for 170.9 million rand. Pinnacle  
 SABMiller Plc  (SAB SJ), the world’s second-largest brewer,
dropped 3.25 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 218.75 rand. The brewer
was downgraded to “equal weight” from “overweight” at
Barclays Capital.  
